    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-09-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-09-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="1445"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1445">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.00/2039.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of the Navy</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Navy Department</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-09-28">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 28, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to invite attention to the
                    telegram from the American Minister at Managua, dated 11 p.m., September 26th,
                    transmitting a message for the Secretary of the Navy from the
                    Commander-in-Chief, Pacific Fleet, dated September 26th, 9 p.m., and
                    particularly to the following portion thereof: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Please request Governor of Canal Zone to permit his [Mena’s] landing. I
                            suggest that he be kept under surveillance, and that neither he nor his
                            son be allowed to go to any Central American state hereafter. He is sick
                            and unable to walk, may have to be sent to the Ancon hospital.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>This request and suggestion of Rear Admiral Southerland are submitted to the
                    Department of State for its consideration and such <pb facs="1167" n="1051"
                        xml:id="pg_1051"/> action as may be deemed appropriate, attention being
                    invited, in this connection, to the fact that the statements contained in this
                    cablegram indicate that it is possible that the <hi rend="italic">Cleveland</hi>
                    may reach Panama as early as the afternoon of Sunday, September 29th.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Philip Andrews.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
